              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "### Description\n\nThe \"Detected Issue with C Function (malloc)\" vulnerability in C++ typically arises from improper memory allocation practices, such as allocating insufficient memory or failing to check for successful allocation. In the specific case of `malloc(len + 1)`, the vulnerability may occur if `len` is derived from user input or other untrusted sources, leading to potential buffer overflows or memory corruption if the allocated memory is not sufficient for the intended use.\n\n### General Mitigation Advice\n\n1. **Input Validation**: Always validate and sanitize input to ensure it is within expected bounds before using it to determine memory allocation sizes.\n2. **Check Allocation Success**: Always check the return value of `malloc` to ensure that memory allocation was successful before using the allocated memory.\n3. **Use Safer Alternatives**: Consider using safer memory management functions or higher-level abstractions that automatically handle memory allocation and deallocation.\n4. **Boundary Checks**: Ensure that any operations on the allocated memory respect the allocated boundaries to prevent overflows.\n\n### Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```cpp\n#include <cstdlib>\n#include <iostream>\n\nvoid processInput(size_t len) {\n    // Validate input length\n    if (len > SIZE_MAX - 1) {\n        std::cerr << \"Input length is too large.\" << std::endl;\n        return;\n    }\n\n    // Allocate memory with an additional byte for null-termination\n    char* buffer = static_cast<char*>(malloc(len + 1));\n    if (buffer == nullptr) {\n        std::cerr << \"Memory allocation failed.\" << std::endl;\n        return;\n    }\n\n    // Ensure the buffer is null-terminated\n    buffer[len] = '\\0';\n\n    // Use the buffer for intended operations\n    // ...\n\n    // Free the allocated memory\n    free(buffer);\n}\n\nint main() {\n    size_t len = 100; // Example length\n    processInput(len);\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\n### Library Dependencies\n\nTo execute the above code example, the following standard libraries are required:\n\n- `<cstdlib>`: For `malloc` and `free` functions.\n- `<iostream>`: For input/output operations.\n\n### Relevant Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [OWASP Secure Coding Practices](https://owasp.org/www-project-secure-coding-practices-quick-reference-guide/)\n\n### Common Weakness Enumeration\n\n- [CWE-122: Heap-based Buffer Overflow](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/122.html)\n- [CWE-787: Out-of-bounds Write](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/787.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DS161085"
                ]
